(a) Data Heterogeneity  
In my project I worked with three different types of data. The Kaggle cybersecurity incidents dataset was structured data because it looked like a spreadsheet with clear rows and columns such as year, industry, attack type. The CVE data I pulled from the NVD API was semi‑structured because it came in JSON format. It had fields like cve_id, description, published date, but the structure was nested and not always the same for every record. The Google Trends data was more unstructured because it only gave me relative interest scores over time, like “ransomware = 75” or “data breach = 60,” without much context. So my pipeline combined structured, semi‑structured, and unstructured data, which shows heterogeneity.

(b) Extraction Challenges  
Each source had its own challenges. With the NVD API, I faced issues when the endpoint returned errors or when the JSON structure was slightly different than expected. I had to add error handling to make sure the pipeline didn’t break. With Kaggle, the challenge was that the dataset is static, so I had to download it manually and it doesn’t update automatically like an API. With Google Trends, the difficulty was that it only gives relative scores from 0 to 100, not actual search counts, and sometimes the data comes back incomplete. These differences meant I had to adjust my extraction code for each source.

(c) Storage Justification  
I stored the data in both CSV and JSON formats because each format has its own strengths. CSV is simple and works well when I want to analyze the data in tools like Excel, pandas, or SQL, since it is just rows and columns. JSON is better when I want to keep the nested structure from APIs, because it preserves the hierarchy and is easier to share with web applications. For example, the Kaggle dataset fits naturally into CSV, while the CVE API data makes more sense in JSON. Having both formats gives flexibility: CSV for analysis and reporting, JSON for keeping the original structure and working with applications.